I was pondering what <@U286Q175Y> said Friday about coming up with a new niche in commander gameplay, so I came up with this.

The idea is to run Grand Melee using EDH decks. Play with a reach of 1 to maximize the number of simultaneous turns being taken. Then when down to 5 players taking only the 1 turn, transition to "regular" FFA commander.
<https://mtg.gamepedia.com/Grand_Melee>
It would have a distinct identity that could be tied to EDHREC, but still recognizable as EDH.
That... actually sounds like it would make for fairly good television.
Would probably need to ban extra turns to keep things flowing smoothly.
Don't want 30 people sitting still while waiting for someone to take 3 turns in a row.
It's a lot of fun.  :slightly_smiling_face: My best friend and I would go around to local cons in the mid 90s to play tournaments, chat up the organizers and other players to get them going.
We'd go to the vendor tables and ask them to chip in prizes, so people would get excited. Everyone was always happy to help out.
Honestly, the more I think about it the more I really like that idea. <@U286Q175Y>, what do you think?
For something more formal, like Don's travelling show, going to small conventions with a dedicated filming crew seems more viable than going to stores.
And as people got bumped out, they could be interviewed with questions like, "What was your craziest play?" "How'd you get eliminated?" etc.
So you're generating youtube content  I guess, and getting ad revenue that way?
Not sure what the logistics of formally running an event at a con are. Can you charge for participation separately from the entrance fee?
Typically you can, as long as you can justify it
That's easy, prize pool.

Something we did was to award points for eliminating people, to promote a more aggressive game. The winner was the winner and got the grand prize, but then the rest of the prizes would be distributed based on points acquired.
Obviously the meta for these decks would be different, but that's okay.
Oh, and you only got point for eliminating your attack target on the left. If you eliminated the person behind you through non-combat means, you're giving the person behind them a point.
